Cats in R??? What?


Really?

Yup

  • cat() stands for Concatenate and Print
  • It’s is a function to output objects to the console
  • Doesn’t do as much conversion as print. Still powerful

Using cat()

cat(..., file="catData.txt"" sep= "\n", append=TRUE)

  • args:
    • … - The information to be printed out to the screen
    • file - An optional argument that specifics a file to be created, overwritten, or appended
    • sep - Specifies what separates the printed objects
    • append - Boolean: If a file is to be appended or not, defaults to FALSE
  • Canonical Examples:
    • http://rfunction.com/archives/1866

Using cat() (con’t)

x<- c(25, 50, 75, 100)
cat(x, sep = " . ") 
## 25 . 50 . 75 . 100
cat(x, sep = "\n") # "\n" is a newline character
## 25
## 50
## 75
## 100

Using cat() (con’t)

  • More complex data structures such as nested lists don’t work
y <- list(a = c(1, 2, 3), b = list(name = "Bob", age = 55, 
    gender = "male"))
# Will fail: cat(y) Instead:
cat(str(y))
## List of 2
##  $ a: num [1:3] 1 2 3
##  $ b:List of 3
##   ..$ name  : chr "Bob"
##   ..$ age   : num 55
##   ..$ gender: chr "male"

Using cat() (con’t)

x <- c(25, 50, 75, 100)
for (i in 1:length(x)) {
    if (i == 1) {
        cat("Starting some operation", "\n")
    }
    cat(paste0("The value in position ", i, " of the object x is ", 
        x[i]), "\n")
    if (i == length(x)) {
        cat("Process completed. Processed", length(x), "values", 
            "\n")
    }
}
## Starting some operation 
## The value in position 1 of the object x is 25 
## The value in position 2 of the object x is 50 
## The value in position 3 of the object x is 75 
## The value in position 4 of the object x is 100 
## Process completed. Processed 4 values

How I most commonly use cat() in R…

  • Monitoring the progress of RScript functions
  • Debugging shiny applications:
    • https://shiny.rstudio.com/articles/debugging.html
      • see the part about printf tracing
      • “In some situations the best tracing technique is the oldest: a statement that emits text to the console when it’s reached. These are more work to use, but offer the unique advantage of allowing you to emit the values of variables without interrupting execution.”
  • Demo time

RScript

Steps To Run (Mac/Linux):
1. Copy the catRscript code in the appendix into a new file, call it catRscript.R
2. Save the file to your current working directory
3. Open a terminal window
4. cd to the directory from step 2
5. Type Rscript catRscript.R and press enter

Appendix

  • Code for the Rscript example:
x <- c(25, 50, 75, 100)
for (i in 1:length(x)) {
    if (i == 1) {
        cat("Starting some operation", "\n")
    }
    cat(paste0("The value in position ", i, " of the object x is ", 
        x[i]), "\n")
    if (i == length(x)) {
        cat("Process completed. Processed", length(x), "values", 
            "\n")
    }
    Sys.sleep(2)
}
